3. add "starter" tier (< $49) and "enterprise" tier (> $49)
4. introduce free plan

He recommends introducing a free plan at this stage. And his approach is to do this to discourage competition.

IMHO this is a great pricing strategy for a yet to launch or just launched SaaS.

2. "ship 100+ features, raise to $49"
Ryan clarified  $49 is X*2.5 where X is the paid tier from step 1.

You are providing more value so increasing the price makes sense.
Ryan suggests grandfathering early users This could be a hook for users to sign-up early.

1. Launch with a one paid tier with - No free tier at this stage.

The reasoning behind this is to get the right kind of customers on-board in the beginning.  Getting lots of free tier users might skew your product/market fit. The free tier has a place, but not in the beginning.

My takeaways from the SaaS pricing tweet from @ryanckulp
